item.label: Post-olivary sulcus
item.name: Postolivary sulcus
item.description: On the ventral-lateral aspect of the medulla, the post-olivary sulcus is located between the olive and the tuberculum cinereum.  The glossopharyngeal and vagus nerve branches enter/exit the brainstem in this sulcus.

item.label: Pre-olivary sulcus
item.name: Preolivary sulcus
item.description: On the ventral aspect of the medulla, the pre-olivary sulcus lies between the pyramid and the olive.  The rootlets of the hypoglossal cranial nerve exit the brainstem along this sulcus.

item.label: Sulcus limitans
item.name: Sulcus limitans
item.description: The sulcus limitans is a shallow groove in the floor of the fourth ventricle that demarcates sensory cranial nerve nuclei (laterally) from motor cranial nerve nuclei (medially). Embryonically, it is a longitudinal groove extending along the length of the brain stem and spinal cord, separating alar plate (future sensory nuclei) from basal plate (future motor nuclei.)

item.label: Ventral median fissure
item.name: Ventral median fissure
item.description: The ventral median fissure of the spinal cord is AKA the anterior median fissure. It is a deep fissure separating the two ventral or anterior columns of the spinal cord. This fissure extends into the medulla and stops at the caudal aspect of the pons. It is interrupted by pyramidal decussation at the junction of the spinal cord with the medulla.

item.label: Cerebellum, cortex
item.name: Cerebellum, cortex
item.description: The outer cortical surface of the cerebellum is folded into fine-caliber ridges called folia.  This cortex consists of three layers, an outer molecular layer, an inner granular layer and a Purkinje cell layer in the middle at the junction of the molecular and granular layers.

item.label: Inferior cerebellar peduncle
item.name: Inferior cerebellar peduncle
item.description: The inferior cerebellar peduncle is AKA the restiform body. Located on the lateral aspect of the medulla, it includes multiple tracts afferent to the cerebellum including the uncrossed dorsal or posterior spinocerebellar, cuneocerebellar, vestibulocerebellar, reticulocerebellar and crossed olivocerebellar. It also includes some cerebellar output tracts such as those projecting to the reticular formation and the vestibular nuclei.

item.label: Arcuate nucleus
item.name: Arcuate nucleus
item.description: The arcuate nucleus of the medulla is a small group of neurons located on the anterior surface of the medullary pyramids.  Rostrally, they appear to be continuous with the pontine nuclei in the basilar pons.  These neurons receive corticospinal tract input and send their output through the anterior or ventral external arcuate fibers and the stria medullares in the floor of the fourth ventricle to the cerebellum via the inferior cerebellar peduncle.

item.label: Cochlear nuclei
item.name: Cochlear nuclei
item.description: Dorsal and ventral cochlear nuclei are located lateral to the inferior cerebellar peduncle at the level of the pons/medulla junction. They receive primary sensory input from the hair cell receptors of the cochlea via the eighth (cochlear or auditory) cranial nerve. Efferents from the cochlear nuclei project to the superior olivary nuclei and into the lateral lemniscus where they will synapse in the inferior colliculus of the midbrain.

item.label: Cochlear nucleus, dorsal
item.name: Cochlear nucleus, dorsal
item.description: Dorsal and ventral cochlear nuclei are located lateral to the inferior cerebellar peduncle at the level of the pons/medulla junction. They receive primary sensory input from the hair cell receptors of the cochlea via the eighth (cochlear or auditory) cranial nerve. Efferents from the cochlear nuclei project to the superior olivary nuclei and into the lateral lemniscus where they will synapse in the inferior colliculus of the midbrain.

item.label: Cochlear nucleus, ventral
item.name: Cochlear nucleus, ventral
item.description: Dorsal and ventral cochlear nuclei are located lateral to the inferior cerebellar peduncle at the level of the pons/medulla junction. They receive primary sensory input from the hair cell receptors of the cochlea via the eighth (cochlear or auditory) cranial nerve. Efferents from the cochlear nuclei project to the superior olivary nuclei and into the lateral lemniscus where they will synapse in the inferior colliculus of the midbrain.

item.label: Dorsal motor nucleus of vagus
item.name: Dorsal motor nucleus of vagus
item.description: The dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus is a parasympathetic cranial nerve nucleus located along the ventricular surface of the open medulla. Sandwiched between the hypoglossal motor nucleus, medially and the sensory solitary nucleus, laterally. Origin of most preganglionic parasympathetic fibers traveling to the thoracic and abdominal viscera via the vagus nerve.

item.label: Hypoglossal nucleus
item.name: Hypoglossal nucleus
item.description: The long, thin hypoglossal nucleus is the origin of the hypoglossal cranial nerve. It is located in the dorsomedial aspect of the medulla immediately beneath the surface of the fourth ventricle. It is the nucleus closest to the midline with the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus located lateral it. It innervates the ipsilateral intrinsic and extrinsic skeletal muscles of the tongue.

item.label: Inferior olivary nuclear complex
item.name: Inferior olivary nuclear complex
item.description: The inferior olivary complex consists of the large inferior olivary nucleus (AKA the principal olivary nucleus) plus the dorsal and medial accessory olivary nuclei.  Together they are responsible for the large 'olive' on the lateral aspect of the medulla.  The output of this nuclear complex consists of 'climbing fibers' that project to the contralateral cerebellum.  The principal inferior olivary nucleus projects to the hemispheres of the cerebellum while the accessory nuclei project to the vermis and flocculus of the cerebellum.  Note that the superior olivary nucleus is NOT part of this nuclear complex, but rather is associated with the auditory pathway.

item.label: Inferior olivary nucleus
item.name: Inferior olivary nucleus
item.description: The inferior olivary nucleus is a large, convoluted, drawstring purse-like nucleus in the anterolateral medulla.  It receives multiple afferents from the spinal cord, red nucleus, cerebellum, etc. It projects to the contralateral cerebellum via olivocerebellar fibers that travel in the contralateral inferior cerebellar peduncle to terminate as climbing fibers in the cerebellum. Can be confused with the dentate nucleus in the cerebellum because of its similar appearance.

item.label: Dorsal accessory olivary nucleus
item.name: Dorsal accessory olivary nucleus
item.description: The inferior olivary complex consists of the large inferior olivary nucleus (AKA the principal olivary nucleus) plus the dorsal and medial accessory olivary nuclei.  Together they are responsible for the large 'olive' on the lateral aspect of the medulla.  The output of this nuclear complex consists of 'climbing fibers' that project to the contralateral cerebellum.  The principal inferior olivary nucleus projects to the hemispheres of the cerebellum while the accessory nuclei project to the vermis and flocculus of the cerebellum.  Note that the superior olivary nucleus is NOT part of this nuclear complex, but rather is associated with the auditory pathway.

item.label: Medial accessory olivary nucleus
item.name: Medial accessory olivary nucleus
item.description: The inferior olivary complex consists of the large inferior olivary nucleus (AKA the principal olivary nucleus) plus the dorsal and medial accessory olivary nuclei.  Together they are responsible for the large 'olive' on the lateral aspect of the medulla.  The output of this nuclear complex consists of 'climbing fibers' that project to the contralateral cerebellum.  The principal inferior olivary nucleus projects to the hemispheres of the cerebellum while the accessory nuclei project to the vermis and flocculus of the cerebellum.  Note that the superior olivary nucleus is NOT part of this nuclear complex, but rather is associated with the auditory pathway.

item.label: Nucleus ambiguus
item.name: Nucleus ambiguus
item.description: The nucleus ambiguus is a cranial nerve nucleus that exists as a column of neurons in the medulla, embedded within the reticular formation and located somewhat medial to the spinothalamic tract. It contains lower motor neurons of the glossopharyngeal and vagal nerves that innervate the laryngeal and pharyngeal musculature as well as parasympathetic pre-ganglionic neurons that innervate the heart via the vagus nerve.

item.label: Raphe nuclei
item.name: Raphe nuclei
item.description: The raphe nuclei are a series of brainstem nuclei located near the midline of the tegmentum. Important among these is the nucleus raphe magnus since it is the origin of the raphe spinal tract that blocks or modulates pain sensation at the level of the dorsal horn of the spinal cord.

item.label: Reticular formation
item.name: Reticular formation
item.description: Reticular formation is the central region of the brainstem tegmentum (medulla, pons, midbrain).  It is a network of interconnected nuclei and nerve fibers. Due to its widespread afferent and efferent connections, it serves a major integrating function. It gives origin to clinically significant tracts such as the reticulospinal and raphe spinal. It contains the cardiovascular and respiratory centers so critical to survival. It is also an important component of the sleep/wake cycle via is role in the ascending reticular activating system.

item.label: Solitary nucleus
item.name: Solitary nucleus
item.description: The solitary nucleus is a visceral sensory nucleus in the medulla & caudal pons located as a thin column of cells just lateral to the sulcus limitans in the floor of the fourth ventricle and surrounding the solitary tract. The rostral portion of the nucleus is AKA the gustatory nucleus since it receives primary afferent taste input via the facial, glossopharyngeal and possibly the vagal nerves; this part of the nucleus is considered special visceral afferent (SVA). The caudal portion of the nucleus receives primary general visceral afferent (GVA) input from the viscera, aortic and carotid barareceptors, etc over the glossopharyngeal and vagal nerves.

item.label: Trigeminal spinal nucleus
item.name: Trigeminal spinal nucleus
item.description: The trigeminal spinal nucleus is AKA the spinal trigeminal nucleus. It is a portion of the trigeminal sensory nuclei that exists as a longitudinal column of cells within the lateral aspect of the caudal pons and medulla. Caudally, it merges with the dorsal horn of the spinal cord (particularly, the substantia gelatinosa); rostrally it merges into the trigeminal main sensory nucleus. It consists of second-order sensory neurons that receive primarily pain and temperature information from the head via input from the trigeminal spinal (or spinal trigeminal) tract. Efferents from this nucleus terminate in the contralateral ventral posterior medial nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Vestibular nuclei
item.name: Vestibular nuclei
item.description: The vestibular nuclei are a group of four sub-nuclei present bilaterally in the floor of the fourth ventricle at the junction of the pons and medulla. The four sub-nuclei are the inferior, lateral, medial and superior. These nuclei receive input from the vestibular organs (cristae of the semicircular ducts and maculae of the utricle and saccule of the inner ear) via the eighth cranial nerve. These nuclei project to the nuclei innervating the extraocular muscles via the medial longitudinal fasciculus, to the cerebellum, to the spinal cord, thalamus and reticular formation.

item.label: Vestibular nucleus, medial
item.name: Vestibular nucleus, medial
item.description: The vestibular nuclei are a group of four sub-nuclei present bilaterally in the floor of the fourth ventricle at the junction of the pons and medulla. The four sub-nuclei are the inferior, lateral, medial and superior. These nuclei receive input from the vestibular organs (cristae of the semicircular ducts and maculae of the utricle and saccule of the inner ear) via the eighth cranial nerve. These nuclei project to the nuclei innervating the extraocular muscles via the medial longitudinal fasciculus, to the cerebellum, to the spinal cord, thalamus and reticular formation.

item.label: Vestibular nucleus, inferior
item.name: Vestibular nucleus, inferior
item.description: The vestibular nuclei are a group of four sub-nuclei present bilaterally in the floor of the fourth ventricle at the junction of the pons and medulla. The four sub-nuclei are the inferior, lateral, medial and superior. These nuclei receive input from the vestibular organs (cristae of the semicircular ducts and maculae of the utricle and saccule of the inner ear) via the eighth cranial nerve. These nuclei project to the nuclei innervating the extraocular muscles via the medial longitudinal fasciculus, to the cerebellum, to the spinal cord, thalamus and reticular formation.

item.label: Corticospinal/Corticobulbar tract
item.name: Corticospinal_Corticobulbar tract
item.description: These descending motor tracts originate in the cerebral cortex and then travel through the posterior limb of the internal capsule, the cerebral crus of the midbrain, the basilar portion of the pons and the pyramids of the medulla.  Sometimes this group of tracts is referred to as the pyramidal tract or system.  It includes the corticospinal, corticobulbar and corticopontine tracts.  The corticopontine fibers terminate at the level of the pons; therefore, the pyramids contain only corticospinal and corticobulbar fibers while only the corticospinal fibers continue into the spinal cord.  There are other subcortical descending motor tracts (reticulospinal and vestibulospinal) that originate in the reticular formation and vestibular nuclei of the brain stem.

item.label: Dorsal longitudinal fasciculus
item.name: Dorsal longitudinal fasciculus
item.description: The dorsal longitudinal fasciculus consists of ascending and descending fibers traveling through the periaqueductal and periventricular gray matter, connecting the hypothalamus to the reticular formation and to preganglionic autonomic neurons.

item.label: Inferior cerebellar peduncle
item.name: Inferior cerebellar peduncle2
item.description: The inferior cerebellar peduncle is AKA the restiform body. Located on the lateral aspect of the medulla, it includes multiple tracts afferent to the cerebellum including the uncrossed dorsal or posterior spinocerebellar, cuneocerebellar, vestibulocerebellar, reticulocerebellar and crossed olivocerebellar. It also includes some cerebellar output tracts such as those projecting to the reticular formation and the vestibular nuclei.

item.label: Medial lemniscus
item.name: Medial lemniscus
item.description: The medial lemniscus is the primary ascending tract carrying tactile, vibratory and proprioceptive information from the body through the brainstem. Cells of origin are in the contralateral cuneate and gracile nuclei; termination is in the ventral posterior lateral nucleus of the thalamus. Comparable input from the head is carried in trigeminothalamic tract fibers that accompany the medial lemniscus but terminate in the ventral posterior medial nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Medial longitudinal fasciculus
item.name: Medial longitudinal fasciculus
item.description: The medial longitudinal fasciculus is an important ascending fiber bundle involved in the coordination of horizontal eye movements through its origin in the vestibular nuclei and termination in the oculomotor and abducens nuclei. It is an important component of the VOR (vestibulo-ocular) reflex. A descending component of this tract (AKA medial vestibulospinal tract) travels to cervical levels of the cord and is involved in turning of the head in response to vestibular stimulation.

item.label: Olivocerebellar tract
item.name: Olivocerebellar tract
item.description: The olivocerebellar tract originates in the inferior olivary nuclei with its axons decussating within the medulla to enter the contralateral cerebellum via the inferior cerebellar peduncle.  The axons in this tract terminate as climbing fibers within the cerebellum.  Note that as these nerve fibers cross the medulla, they are sometimes referred to as internal arcuate fibers; these should not be confused with the internal arcuate fibers that originate in the dorsal column nuclei and decussate to form the medial lemniscus.

item.label: Solitary tract
item.name: Solitary tract
item.description: The solitary tract is located in the medulla and caudal pons, surrounded by the solitary nucleus, it consists of primary afferent or first order fibers carrying taste input via the facial, glossopharyngeal and possibly the vagal nerves to the rostral aspect of the solitary nucleus (SVA) and general visceral input via the glossopharyngeal and vagal nerves (GVA) to the caudal aspect of the solitary nucleus.

item.label: Spinocerebellar tract, ventral
item.name: Spinocerebellar tract, ventral
item.description: The ventral or anterior spinocerebellar tract carries proprioceptive information from neurons in the dorsal aspect of the ventral horn in the thoracic-lumbar spinal cord to the ipsilateral cerebellum. The tract decussates in the ventral white commissure near its origin and is then located in the ventral-lateral aspect of the lateral column of the spinal cord, contralateral to the side of input. This tract takes a circuitous route to cerebellum via the superior cerebellum peduncle and recrosses the midline within the white matter of the cerebellum so that it terminates ipsilateral to the original side of input. The information in this tract comes from proprioceptors in the ipsilateral lower extremity that send their input via large diameter primary afferents to terminate or synapse in the dorsal aspect of the ventral horn.

item.label: Spinothalamic tract
item.name: Spinothalamic tract
item.description: The spinothalamic tract is primarily responsible for transmitting nociceptive (pain) and temperature information from the body. Small diameter primary afferents (first order neurons) bring the pain and temperature information into the ipsilateral dorsal horn where they synapse on the cells of origin of the spinothalamic tract. The second order neurons in the dorsal horn send their axons across the midline in the ventral white commissure so that the spinothalmamic tract ascends in the anterolateral portion of the spinal cord contralateral to the side of input of the information. This tract terminates in the ventral posterior lateral nucleus (VPL) of thalamus. From this thalamic nucleus, the information is carried to the primary somatosensory cerebral cortex where the sensation is consciously perceived.

item.label: Tectospinal tract
item.name: Tectospinal tract
item.description: The tectospinal tract originates in the superior colliculus and terminates in the cervical spinal cord. Its fibers end via interneurons on ventral horn neurons that primarily supply muscles in the neck.

item.label: Trigeminal spinal tract
item.name: Trigeminal spinal tract
item.description: The trigeminal spinal tract is AKA spinal trigeminal tract. It consists of small-diameter primary afferent nerve fibers carrying primarily pain and temperature information from the head via the trigeminal nerve (primarily) as well as the facial and glossopharyngeal nerves. The trigeminal spinal (or spinal trigeminal) tract fibers synapse in the trigeminal spinal (or spinal trigeminal) nucleus. Note that in the transition region from spinal cord to medulla, Lissauer's tract becomes continuous with the trigeminal spinal tract.

item.label: Cochlear nerve
item.name: Cochlear nerve
item.description: The cochlear nerve is AKA the auditory nerve. This portion of the eighth cranial nerve enters the brainstem at the cerebellopontine angle along with the vestibular nerve. It carries information from the hair cell receptors in the organ of Corti of the cochlear duct of the inner ear to the cochlear nuclei located at the pons/medulla junction. The term vestibulocochlear nerve refers to the entire eighth cranial nerve -- both vestibular and auditory components.

Efferents from the cochlear nuclei project to the superior olivary nuclei and into the lateral lemniscus where they will synapse in the inferior colliculus of the midbrain.

item.label: Dorsal motor nucleus of vagus
item.name: Dorsal motor nucleus of vagus_1
item.description: The dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus is a parasympathetic cranial nerve nucleus located along the ventricular surface of the open medulla. Sandwiched between the hypoglossal motor nucleus, medially and the sensory solitary nucleus, laterally. Origin of most preganglionic parasympathetic fibers traveling to the thoracic and abdominal viscera via the vagus nerve.

item.label: Facial nerve
item.name: Facial nerve
item.description: The facial or seventh cranial nerve has both sensory and motor components which enter/exit the brain stem in the cerebellopontine angle with the vestibulocochlear nerve. The most important sensory component carries taste from the anterior 2/3rds of the tongue; motor components innervate the skeletal muscles of facial expression, stapedius, etc. as well as provide the parasympathetic preganglionic fibers that control secretion of the submandibular, sublingual and lacrimal glands.

item.label: Hypoglossal nerve
item.name: Hypoglossal nerve
item.description: The twelfth or hypoglossal cranial nerve is purely motor and innervates the ipsilateral intrinsic and extrinsic skeletal muscles of the tongue (except for the palatoglossus). It exits the medulla as a series of rootlets in the ventral lateral or anterolateral fissure between the olive and the pyramid in the medulla.

item.label: Hypoglossal nucleus
item.name: Hypoglossal nucleus_1
item.description: The long, thin hypoglossal nucleus is the origin of the hypoglossal cranial nerve. It is located in the dorsomedial aspect of the medulla immediately beneath the surface of the fourth ventricle. It is the nucleus closest to the midline with the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus located lateral it. It innervates the ipsilateral intrinsic and extrinsic skeletal muscles of the tongue.

item.label: Trigeminal spinal nucleus
item.name: Trigeminal spinal nucleus_1
item.description: The trigeminal spinal nucleus is AKA the spinal trigeminal nucleus. It is a portion of the trigeminal sensory nuclei that exists as a longitudinal column of cells within the lateral aspect of the caudal pons and medulla. Caudally, it merges with the dorsal horn of the spinal cord (particularly, the substantia gelatinosa); rostrally it merges into the trigeminal main sensory nucleus. It consists of second-order sensory neurons that receive primarily pain and temperature information from the head via input from the trigeminal spinal (or spinal trigeminal) tract. Efferents from this nucleus terminate in the contralateral ventral posterior medial nucleus of the thalamus.

item.label: Vestibular nerve
item.name: Vestibular nerve
item.description: The vestibular portion of the eighth cranial nerve enters the brainstem at the cerebellopontine angle along with the auditory portion of the eight nerve. It carries information from the hair cell receptors in the vestibular organs (cristae of the semicircular ducts and maculae of the utricle and saccule of the inner ear).

The four sub-nuclei are the inferior, lateral, medial and superior. These nuclei project to the nuclei innervating the extraocular muscles via the medial longitudinal fasciculus, to the cerebellum, to the spinal cord, thalamus and reticular formation.

The four sub-nuclei are the inferior, lateral, medial and superior. item.name: Vestibular nucleus, inferior2

The four sub-nuclei are the inferior, lateral, medial and superior. These nuclei project to the nuclei innervating the extraocular muscles via the medial longitudinal fasciculus, to the cerebellum, to the spinal cord, thalamus and reticular formation.

item.label: Inferior medullary velum
item.name: Inferior medullary velum
item.description: The inferior medullary velum is a very thin membrane that forms part of the roof of the fourth ventricle caudal to the peak of the ventricle.  It contains the choroid plexus of the fourth ventricle.  The foramen of Magendie (medial foramen) is an opening in this structure that allows cerebrospinal fluid to leave the fourth ventricle and enter the subarachnoid space.

item.label: Fourth Ventricle
item.name: Fourth Ventricle
item.description: The fourth ventricle is a rhomboid-shaped space located superior to the pons and medulla. The roof of the fourth ventricle is formed by the inferior and superior medullary vela plus the cerebellum. Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) enters the fourth ventricle from the third ventricle via the cerebral aqueduct. CSF exits the fourth ventricle into the subarachnoid space via the medial foramen of Magendie, located in the roof of the fourth ventricle, and the two lateral foramina of Luschka, located at the most lateral aspect of the fourth ventricle, i.e. in the lateral recess of the fourth ventricle, bilaterally.  The choroid plexus is located in the roof of the fourth ventricle, beneath the inferior medullary velum.  The choroid plexus extends outside of the fourth ventricle through the foramina of Luschka, where it can be visualized in the subarachnoid space.

item.label: Choroid plexus
item.name: Choroid plexus
item.description: The choroid plexus is the convoluted and highly vascularized structure in the ventricles that is responsible for the production of cerebrospinal fluid.  It is located in the floor of the lateral ventricle as it curves from the body of the ventricle into the inferior horn; it is not present in the anterior or posterior horns of the lateral ventricle.  From the lateral ventricle, the choroid plexus extends through the interventricular foramina of Monro onto the roof of the third ventricle.  In the fourth ventricle the choroid plexus extends downward from the inferior medullary velum that forms part of the roof the ventricle.  The choroid plexus also extends from the fourth ventricle through the foramina of Luschka into the subarachnoid space.

item.label: Sulcus limitans
item.name: Sulcus limitans_1
item.description: The sulcus limitans is a shallow groove in the floor of the fourth ventricle that demarcates sensory cranial nerve nuclei (laterally) from motor cranial nerve nuclei (medially). Embryonically, it is a longitudinal groove extending along the length of the brain stem and spinal cord, separating alar plate (future sensory nuclei) from basal plate (future motor nuclei.)
